column2: Near shore plants dying back; leafy weeds with seed stalks.  Lily pads past bloom.
Near Shore plants:  only pads and cattails remain.  Plant survey done today by Tim Hoyman of NES Ecological Services- Green Bay.  Part of a grant/project for Manitowoc County Lake Assoc.
Near shore plants: Lily pads dying back.
White lily pads (l. pads) blooming.  Some algae in shoreline weeds.
White lily pads blooming/ yellow starting.  Submersed grassy weeds apparent.  Coontail at surface.
White and yellow lily pads blooming.  2 free floating patches (1x2 feet) of algae with coontail strings (new!).
Lotsa coontail near shore.  Also some old dead "crusty" beds near shore.  Thick pondweed.
Longleaf pondweed showing seed stalks.  Huge coontail beds.  Pondweed (thin leaf / gassy) browning.
Coontail decay start.  Long leaf pondweed past bloom.  White lily pads starting to bloom.
Some late lily pad blooms.  Coontail decaying / floating patches.  Small pumpkinseed fish on south shore weed line (new).
Lily pads 90% gone.  Other plants gone.  Minnows gone - usually very plentiful all summer.  Infeed creek from highway culvert dry all summer.  No flow except spring thaw and one storm.
Pads blooming.  Broadleaf weeds showing seed heads.  Coontail in full growth.
Some pads yet blooming.  Coontail brown and fading.
Lake level very low- at least 12"-16" below normal.  7 feet of bank showing.
White pads blooming- Preponderance of elodia  Plants. Brown Pondweed with 1-2" seed spike- all weeds have a "flour like" dusty coating.
Few white pad blooms- cootail in near growth near shore. Elodia  Still prominant/dusty.
Coontail decay starting; large floating patches. Pads starting to brown; scarce blooms.
White pads blooming.  Waterweed dying off.  Coontail plentiful.  Cattails and pondweed have seed heads.
Pads dying back.  Cattails shedding wooly seed heads.
